<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-inverse-variation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Inverse Variation and Negative Exponent Activities</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
        Recall that in <xref ref="sec-inverse-variation-prep"/>, we said that two varying quantities <m>Q_1</m> and <m>Q_2</m> have an <term>inversely proportional relationship</term> when the product of the quantities is constant. That is, <m>Q_1</m> and <m>Q_2</m> have an inversely proportional relationship when 
      <me>
        c = Q_2 Q_1
      </me>
      always has the same value. We call <m>c</m> the <term>constant of proportionality</term>.
    </p>
    <p>
        We sometimes reorganize <m>c = Q_2 Q_1</m> as
        <me>
           Q_2 = \frac{c}{Q_1} 
        </me>
        and say that <m>Q_2</m> <term>varies inversely</term> with respect to <m>Q_1</m>.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <activity xml:id="a-zipf-law-en-wikipedia">
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Zipf's Law says that in a particular text, the number of times a word appears in the text is inversely proportional to its rank (i.e., the most common word has rank 1, the second most common has rank 2, etc.). Let <m>N</m> be the number of times, in millions, a word appears in English Wikipedia and <m>r</m> be its rank.
        </p>
        <p>
            According to one source<fn><url href="https://github.com/IlyaSemenov/wikipedia-word-frequency" /></fn>, <q>the</q> was the most common word in English Wikipedia in 2023, appearing 187 times. 
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
           What are the values of <m>r</m> and <m>N</m> for <q>the</q> in English Wikipedia?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use your values of <m>r</m> and <m>N</m> to find the constant of proportionality.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Set up a formula that outputs <m>N</m> when given <m>r</m>. That is, write a formula that relates <m>r</m> and <m>N</m> where <m>N</m> is by itself on one side of the equals sign, and the other side of the equations sign is an expression that includes <m>r</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Use your formula to estimate the number of times each of the following words appears in English Wikipedia:
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <q>of</q>, the second most common word
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <q>is</q>, the eight most common word
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In fact, <q>of</q> occurred 88.3 million times and <q>is</q> occurred 24 million times. Does your model seem to give reasonable estimates, based on these two data points?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The word <q>were</q> occurred 8.7 million times. Use your model to predict its rank. (It was really 21st. How good was your prediction?)
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </activity>

  <!-- Scenario suggested by Gemini. Gemini also created the data table, which seems to be reasonable based on relatively quick confirmation searching. -->
  <activity xml:id="a-wifi-strength-distance">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Have you ever noticed that your wi-fi signal strength gets worse as you get further away from the router? Aliyah, an engineering student, is experimenting with a wireless router to learn more about the relationship between signal strength and distance. She's measuring signal strength in milliwatts (mW), because she's knows that's more accurate than the more commonly reported dBm or RSSI values. The table below gives her data.
      </p>
      <table>
        <title>Wi-Fi Signal Power (in mW) vs Distance from Router (in meters, m), for a 2.4 GHz Wireless Router</title>
        <tabular halign="center" top="minor" bottom = "minor" right="minor" left="minor">
          <row header="yes">
            <cell>Distance, <m>d</m></cell>
            <cell>Signal Power, <m>s</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>1</cell>
            <cell>0.10000</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>2</cell>
            <cell>0.02500</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>4</cell>
            <cell>0.00625</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>5</cell>
            <cell>0.00400</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>10</cell>
            <cell>0.00100</cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use Aliyah's data to show that signal power and distance aren't inversely proportional.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Aliyah's professor suggested that signal power might vary inversely with the square of distance. Use the data to show that they're correct!
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is the constant of proportionality for the relationship between signal power and the square of distance?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write a formula that shows how signal power varies inversely with the square of distance.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use your formula to predict the signal power from Aliyah's router at a distance of 7 meters.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Some sources suggest that a signal strength of 0.000000001 mW is the minimum strength needed for basic connectivity. How far can Aliyah get from her router and still have at least basic connectivity?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The milliwatt numbers we've been working with in this activity are very small! Why might it be helpful to express them in scientific notation, instead of regular notation?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </activity>

