  <activity xml:id="a-intro-neg-exponents">
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Let's discover another exponent rule.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Use repeated multiplication to rewrite each of the following expressions, then simplify by canceling. Remember, if you cancel everything from the numerator of the fraction, then you're left a <m>1</m> in the numerator.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\frac{x^2}{x^5}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\frac{x^3}{x^7}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </task>
    <task>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Use the Quotient Rule for Exponents to rewrite each of the following expressions as <m>x^{\text{power}}</m>.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\frac{x^2}{x^5}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\frac{x^3}{x^7}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Explain why the last two parts support the reasonableness of the Negative Powers Rule: <me>\frac{1}{x^n} = x^{-n}</me>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
  </activity>

  <activity xml:id="a-rewrite-with-neg-powers">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        The Negative Powers Rule lets us see how inverse proportionality relationships lead to power models.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Rewrite your formula from <xref ref="a-zipf-law-en-wikipedia"/>, relating the number of times a word appears in English Wikipedia and its rank, with a negative exponent to show that it is a power model.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Rewrite your formula from <xref ref="a-wifi-strength-distance"/>, relating the wi-fi signal power and distance from a wireless router, with a negative exponent to show that it is a power model.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </activity>

  <activity xml:id="a-negative-powers-rewrite">
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Let's practice using our new rule, along with other exponent rules, to rewrite expressions.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Rewrite as <m>ax^\text{power}</m>: <m>\frac{6}{x}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Rewrite as <m>ax^\text{power}</m>:<m>\frac{4x^3}{8x^6}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Rewrite without any negative exponents: <m>6^{-1}x^3x^{-5}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Rewrite without any negative exponents: <m>\left(4x^{-6}\right)^{-2}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
  </activity>

  <activity xml:id="a-radar-power-distance">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        A radar system sends out radio waves, which bounce off objects in the world and return to the system. The radar system interprets the signals that it receives back to learn information such as how far away the object. The signal gets weaker the entire time it is traveling. In order for a radar system to detect an object, it has to be close enough that the signal's strength when it arrives back is detectable by the system. Physics tells us that the signal power the system will receive when the signal returns is inversely proportional to the fourth power of the distance the signal has to travel to the object<fn>https://www.radartutorial.eu/01.basics/The%20Radar%20Range%20Equation.en.html</fn>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write an equation for signal power, <m>P</m>, in terms of distance to the object, <m>d</m>. Your equation will have an unknown constant in it!
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The relationship between signal power and distance is a power model. What is its exponent?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose a particular radar system receives a return signal of 4231 picowatts (pW) from a known target 20 kilometers (km) away. Use your equation to find the constant of proportionality. Your answer should be a big number! Write it in scientific notation, and round so that there are 2 decimal places in scientific notation.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What signal power should this system receive back from a target that is 25 km away?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose that the smallest signal that this radar system can detect is 100 pW. What is the maximum distance at which this system can detect an object?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </activity>

  <activity xml:id="a-adv-exponent-rules-practice">
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Use your knowledge of exponent rules to rewrite each of the expressions below. 
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Rewrite as <m>ax^{\text{power}}</m>: <m>\frac{5x^3}{x \cdot x^3}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Rewrite without negative exponents: <m>\frac{x^{-8}}{2x^7}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Rewrite without negative exponents: <m>\left(a^{-6} b^2\right)^6</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Rewrite without negative exponents: <m>\left(\frac{8}{x^6}\right)^{-5}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <!-- <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Rewrite without negative or fractional exponents: <m>\left(n^{-8}m^5\right)^{-\frac12}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task> -->
  </activity>

  <activity xml:id="a-color-noise">
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Pink noise is a type of sound that may help some people fall asleep and/or help people with ADHD concentrate.<fn>C. Johnson, <q>Have you tried pink noise for sleep? Here's what to know.</q> AP New, May 20, 2024. <url href="https://apnews.com/article/pink-brown-white-noise-sleep-focus-concentration-f5f24dad1effb09c1cf8b607bd22ebc7"></url></fn> Higher frequency sounds are less intense than low frequency sounds in pink noise. We can model this relationship using the formula <me>P = f^{-1}</me> where <m>P</m> is the power of the sound and <m>f</m> is its frequency.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The two octaves around middle A on a piano have frequencies of about 220 - 880 Hz. Sketch a graph showing the relationship of power to frequency in pink noise for the two octaves around middle A. <alert>Hint:</alert> You don't need to know anything about music to solve this problem. The instructions are telling you that the horizontal axis should start at 220 and go up to 880. Choose some numbers between 220 and 880, plug them into the formula to find the power, and then use these points to make a graph.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Rewrite the formula so that it doesn't have any negative exponents in it.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Complete the sentence: <q>In pink noise, the power of the sounds varies inversely with respect to...</q>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <!--<task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The model for pink noise is also a power model! We can rewrite it as <me>P = f^{-1}</me>. Talk to your table and brainstorm reasons why it might make sense for negative exponents to be related to variables in the denominator of fractions. <alert>Hint:</alert> You thought about this in the prep activities.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>-->
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Brown noise is similar to pink noise, but has the model <me> P = f^{-2} </me> instead. Rewrite this formula without negative exponents.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Complete the sentence: <q>In brown noise, the power of the sound varies inversely with respect to...</q>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Sketch a graph showing the relationship of power to frequency in brown noise for the two octaves around middle A. <alert> Hint: </alert> What steps did you use to sketch a graph for pink noise?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Does pink or brown noise have more power at 220 Hz? at 440 Hz? at 880 Hz?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
  </activity>

